items.name: Mike Mignola Style
items.description:
Mike Mignola is an American comic book artist and writer, best known as the creator of the iconic character Hellboy and the fictional universe surrounding it.

His style can be described as distinctive, dark, and atmospheric. Mignola's artwork often features heavy use of shadows, stark contrasts, and minimalist compositions, creating a sense of mystery and mood in his illustrations.

Mignola's storytelling and visual style draw inspiration from various sources, including folklore, horror, and pulp fiction. He combines elements of supernatural, occult, and mythology to create a unique blend of supernatural adventure and cosmic horror.

Hellboy, Mignola's most famous creation, is a half-demon paranormal investigator with a stone hand and a powerful right hand called the "Right Hand of Doom." The character has become an enduring icon in the comic book world, captivating readers with his complex personality, rich mythology, and the supernatural settings he encounters.

Mignola's artistic vision and storytelling abilities have earned him numerous awards and accolades throughout his career. In addition to his work on Hellboy, he has also contributed to other comic book series and collaborated with various writers and artists.

His influence extends beyond the world of comics, as Mignola's art has inspired film adaptations, animated adaptations, and an expanded universe of Hellboy-related stories and characters.

Mike Mignola's dark and atmospheric art, coupled with his unique storytelling approach, has left an indelible mark on the comic book industry. His contributions to the world of sequential art continue to inspire and entertain fans around the world.

items.name: Peeing pants and other clothes. (Illustrated styles only)
items.description:
This is my wetting LORA trained on 100 images from Gelbooru. It focuses on wetting and can do dark stains. There are no activation words. This works with different models that output drawn images but I found AbyssOrangeMix3 (AOM3) and RevAnimated works really good. It does not work at all with photos as no real images were included in the training data.

For Version 1.0 use "Peeing self" to make sure the image include the character peeing themselves.

For Version 2.0 use "pee stain" instead of "peeing self" if you want to ensure you get dark stains. Add more attention to "pee stain" for bigger pee stains. Add "pee" to the negative prompt if you want to reduce the copious amounts of pee that usually appear without removing the pee stain.

After some more testing I've found between 1 and 1.5 for the LORA weight will generate pee stains on clothing that previously wouldn't have pee stains, and makes the pee stains larger and more well defined. Be aware that changing the weight too much will completely change the image even if you use the same seed.

modelVersions.name: v2.0
modelVersions.description:
• Added "pee stain" to the captions in the dataset which now allows the model to make better pee stains. Also fixed some minor incorrect captions.

  • Discovered how much of a pain it is to edit text files using Google Drive.

It seems like it was only yesterday I released my first pants wetting LORA...oh it was! If you've used it you probably noticed it's not that great at making pee stains. It can do it, but it just doesn't give that massive wet spot us weird fetishists demand. This update now makes large pee stains on most types of clothing. Oddly jeans still exhibit the same behavior as my first version with relatively small pee stains. I can only assume I don't have enough jeans with pee stains in my dataset.

To use this version use "pee stain" to get a wetting with a pee stain. Add more attention to "pee stain" to make the pee stain larger. If you don't like the massive gushers this model sometimes produces add "pee" to the negative prompt to reduce the amount of pee while still maintaining the pee stain. If you want a wetting with a small pee stain use "peeing self". If you use "peeing self" adding "pee" to negative prompts will result in no wetting at all.

Changing the weight on the LORA will change the size of the pee stain and how much pee there is in general. Normally I use 0.7 weight, but for this LORA 1 weight is working out for me. Don't be afraid to play with the weights though.

Just like the previous version I've found that https://civitai.com/models/9942/abyssorangemix3-aom3 works really well with my LORA. Other animated models do work to some degree however.

items.name: Gonzo Wildcards
items.description:
My collection of useful wildcards. Kept updated at: https://github.com/muddylemon/gonzo_wildcards

Usage

Download the zip file and extract the files to:

[your path to]/stable-diffusion-webui/extensions/sd-dynamic-prompts/wildcards/gonzo/

Hit refresh wildcards on the wildcards tab in Stable Diffusion Web UI. You can view the different nodes there and copy the path to the ones you want to use.

Make sure Dynamic Prompts is activated and write a prompt like so:

cartoon drawing of __gonzo/people/hiphop__ , trending on artstation, HD, ((high quality)), vibrant color scheme, character design

and during your render will get something like:

cartoon drawing of Kanye West , trending on artstation, HD, ((high quality)), vibrant color scheme, character design

Combining Wildcards

One section of the wildcards covers famous people divided into collections like popstars, hiphop, billionaires and, of course, useless people... you know the people that are famous for being famous or obnoxious.

A fun combo with the people lists is __gonzo/problems__ which is a list of problems, situations and conundrums. There is also __gonzo/situations__ which contains a variety of places for your mayhem to occur. It's also great for testing embeddings, styles, models, etc on a wide variety of contexts.

Problems Examples

finding a dead body in the basement

forgetting the tickets to a concert

catching a home run ball at a baseball game and throwing it back

peeing their pants in public

getting caught picking their nose

Having their identity stolen

Accidentally deleting an important file

Situations Examples

A bustling metropolis with towering skyscrapers, crowded streets, and neon signs

A serene Japanese garden with koi ponds, stone pathways, and cherry blossoms

A cyberpunk cityscape, with neon signs and holographic advertisements

A quaint, picturesque village with cobblestone streets and charming cottages

An underground cave system filled with stunning crystal formations and glowing minerals

Don't miss __gonzo/holding__ where you can have your characters...

holding a joint

holding a vase

holding a basket

holding a book

holding a cup

Go nuts people!

cartoon drawing of __gonzo/people/hiphop__ __gonzo/problems__ , trending on artstation, HD, ((high quality)), vibrant color scheme, character design

might get you:

cartoon drawing of Eazy-E peeing their pants in public , trending on artstation, HD, ((high quality)), vibrant color scheme, character design

or

cartoon drawing of Cardi B accidentally starting a fire , trending on artstation, HD, ((high quality)), vibrant color scheme, character design

items.name: Ella - Hentai University
items.description:
This is a LoRA for the character Ella, from Hentai University a game by Noodle Jacuzzi.

Ella's art is from the artist Oreteki18kin, the set -

Himari-chan no XXX wa Ooisogashi!

I've been working my way through making these for all the characters currently in the game, and sharing them in the Discord for HU, but figured I should also put them up here.

In general, I'm working from pretty limited image sets, so expect the results to be a bit wonky at times. Ella here, especially. She only has a couple images of just her in the set, everything else is gangbangs and her with another girl.

I recommend a weight of around 0.5, possibly lower depending if you're combining the character LoRA with other styles/costumes/etc. along with tagging some defining characteristics of the character you're generating. Higher than that can really push the artist's original style, and may cause you issues.

All characters I train have a "character tag" added into the set to help generate them fairly reliably.

Recommended LoRA Weight - 0.5 for fairly flexible, higher if you want more of the original artist's style, lower if it doesn't play nice with other loras.

Character tag - HUElla, hair slicked back,
Recommended tags - large breasts, long hair, purple hair, red eyes,

Hair slicked back is pretty much essential if you want her to actually look like she does in the image set.

If you want her bow with the gem, well... Tag "bow, gem". I haven't found a consistent way to get her hairband/bow combo. Oh well. That's what happens with limited data sets.

I've got quite a backlog of these made up already, so I'll be uploading them on and off.

Check my other uploads as I put them out for more HU characters, and if you want any specific character put up soon, let me know.

items.name: General Zod - Superman II - (Actor Terence Stamp)
items.description:
LoRA of General Zod from the 1980 film "Superman II". Trained with Dreambooth using 50 images of actor Terence Stamp portraying Zod in the 1980s movie. The training was done locally using the runpod/local Dreambooth repo by Joe Pena. Resulting CKPT was extracted to LoRA using the A1111 supermerger extension.

Put "Zod Person" in your prompt to trigger it.

For best results use "Hires fix" in the .1 to .3 denoising range (unless using the latent upscalers which you should use higher).

For best results use VAE: vae-ft-mse-840000-ema-pruned.ckpt

For optimal results use Controlnet w/ Openpose/Canny/Reference/Shuffle/etc and reduce the "ending control step" to 50ish or less to guide the image in the right direction.


Trained on SD v1.5 so it should pretty well on any model trained on that as a base. It worked pretty nicely for me using RealisticVision v2, however for best likeness results use the pure SD V1.5 model.

*Note: Many of the sample images were generated with Controlnet - Due to that you may not be able to recreate many of the samples since I use imput images of random film stills (in 16x9ish format) along w/ Openpose/Canny/Shuffle or Reference for ~50 to 60% to direct the output. This limits "double people" from appearing in wider shots, and also prevents the character from being way off in the distance which often doesn't hold the likeness that well. Also: I renamed the LoRA file before uploading it - the name in the metadata on the samples is the same LoRA model.


Thanks to anyone who shares cool/interesting generations they generate w/ this model. It's fun to see and somewhat motivating to try to put some other LoRA/Checkpoints together.

Oh, and now Zod needs machines to fly - Re: samples - :)

items.name: Moebius (Jean Giraud) Style
items.description:
Moebius, also known as Jean Giraud, was a French comic artist and illustrator known for his influential and visionary work in the field of science fiction and fantasy.

His style can be described as highly imaginative, surreal, and characterized by intricate details and organic forms. Moebius was celebrated for his ability to create immersive and visually stunning worlds, transporting readers into realms of imagination.

He co-founded the magazine Métal Hurlant (Heavy Metal) and contributed to other notable publications, including his iconic series "The Incal," created in collaboration with writer Alejandro Jodorowsky. His collaborations extended beyond the realm of comics, working on concept art and storyboarding for films such as "Alien" and "Tron."

Moebius' artwork often featured futuristic landscapes, intricate machinery, and imaginative creatures. His use of bold linework, vibrant colors, and attention to detail created a sense of awe and wonder in his illustrations.

He was admired for his ability to blend science fiction and fantasy elements with philosophical themes, exploring the human condition and the boundaries of reality. Moebius' storytelling and visuals pushed the boundaries of the medium, captivating readers and influencing subsequent generations of artists and creators.

His impact extended beyond the realm of comics and inspired artists, filmmakers, and designers worldwide. Moebius' legacy continues to resonate, with his visionary art and storytelling remaining highly regarded and celebrated in the realms of science fiction, fantasy, and illustration.
